    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "While fingerprint-based identification alone did not exhibit superior effectiveness compared to spectrum-based identification... we explored various combinations of these metrics and evaluated them using the relative ranking performance (RRP)... Utilizing SMSF as the metric to guide the prioritization of matching derivatives led to further enhancement in performance. In the NIST and SWGDRUG data sets, over 90% and 85% of the test substances, respectively, ranked within the top 20 predictions",
      "asbval:note": "Paper does evaluate model outputs across different cohorts (NIST vs SWGDRUG datasets, cathinone vs noncathinone, positive vs negative samples) and reports distributional statistics (ranking performance, sensitivity/specificity by class). However, the paper does not explicitly stratify by 'structural novelty' or use confidence score distributions as the primary analysis method. Instead, it uses ranking metrics (RRP) and similarity scores (SMSF). The stratification is by compound class/dataset type rather than by a continuous structural novelty variable.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c05019",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Stratify a model's prediction outputs (confidence scores, uncertainties) by a categorical grouping variable (e.g., structural novelty, compound class) and compute and visualize distributional statistics to reveal how model behavior varies across cohorts.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:19:48.264607+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Among the 3 false negatives (i.e., MPHP, 4-CL-\u03b1-PVP, and TH-PVP), despite their correct predictions being at high ranks (see Figure 4a), they did not surpass the similarity threshold. The highest similarities of the three false negatives are 0.548, 0.525, and 0.509, respectively... The two false positives PS2MS predicted, MAPDB and MMA, are both amphetamine-like drugs and show highly similar features with cathinone",
      "asbval:note": "Paper does identify systematic prediction failures (false negatives/positives) and notes that structurally similar compounds (amphetamine-like drugs vs cathinone) show degraded discrimination. However, the analysis is not framed as 'confidence degradation across out-of-distribution subsets' but rather as threshold-based classification failures and isomer confusion.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c05019",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill enables detection of systematic prediction bias or confidence degradation in out-of-distribution or novel compound subsets.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:19:48.264607+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "PS2MS employs the DeepEI deep learning model to convert the analyte's mass spectrum into its corresponding fingerprint... A similarity metric based on the fingerprints of both the analyte and its derivatives can then be readily calculated... we explored various combinations of these metrics and evaluated them using the relative ranking performance (RRP)",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses deep learning models (NEIMS, DeepEI) and evaluates on heterogeneous datasets (NIST, SWGDRUG, real-world samples). However, the 'prediction scores' are similarity metrics (cosine, Jaccard, SMSF) and ranking performance (RRP), not softmax probabilities or explicit uncertainty estimates.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c05019",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have prediction scores (softmax probabilities, uncertainties) from a trained deep learning model evaluated on a heterogeneous dataset",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:19:48.264607+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A compound's fingerprint is a binary sequence composed of 0s and 1s, containing structural information that ensures distinct fingerprints for different compounds... The fingerprints of all of the derivatives in the NPS database can be easily transformed using their known structure representation during enumeration.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses molecular fingerprints for stratification and matching, but does not explicitly name RDKit. The paper states fingerprints are computed but does not specify the tool. RDKit is a standard tool for this function, but the paper's actual implementation tool is not named.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c05019",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "RDKit: Compute molecular fingerprints (ECFP) and Tanimoto similarity for structural stratification",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:19:48.264607+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "Paper does not mention PyTorch, TensorFlow, or any deep learning framework. The paper uses NEIMS and DeepEI models but does not specify the implementation framework or how model weights are loaded.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c05019",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "statistical-distribution-analysis-across-cohorts",
